House Price Prediction in Boulder, CO

Xiaoyi Wu

10/20/2021

01. Introduction

1.1 Background

As one of the most popular real estate websites in the United States, Zillow and its affiliates offer customers an on-demand experience for selling, buying, renting and financing with transparency and nearly seamless end-to-end service. These years, Zillow has produced home value reports for the U.S. and over 130 metropolitan statistical areas. The reports identify market trends including, but not limited to: 5- and 10-year annualized change, negative equity, short sales and foreclosure transactions.

However, Zillow has realized that its housing market predictions are not as accurate as they would like. Thus, here, I built a regression model to help Zillow predict the sale price of housing in Boulder County, Colorado between 2019 and 2021.

Here are several main characteristics of the Boulder County housing market:

1. Close proximity to Denver: The Boulder real estate market has all the earmarks of being sustainable. It has benefited a lot from its close proximity to Denver and the employment rate of Boulder County is well above the national average.

2. Abundant landscape features from farmland to rolling grasslands in the plains: Boulder County is close to Rocky Mountains. U.S. Route 36 from Denver with its iconic sandstone slabs rising from the mountains, prefaced by pine-clad mesas and cradled within the backdrop of the snow-capped Indian Peaks provide around 2000 miles of hiking trials and massive green space to Boulder County.

3. Livable metro areas: In the metro area, there are roughly 300,000 people. The district has seen growth as people move from the expensive, over-crowded Denver area to Boulder County where you can still hike in the mountains and see the hills. Boulder County ranks second in Best Places to live for quality of life in U.S. News.

Therefore, considering the characteristics mentioned above, I adopted a geospatial machine learning model to incorporate natural resources distribution and neighborhood effects with socio-economic factors to predict the house prices in various areas of the county.

tracts2019 <- get_acs(geography = "tract", variables = c("B25026_001E","B02001_002E",
                                             "B19013_001E","B25058_001E",
                                             "B06012_002E", 
                                             # vacant variables
                                             "B25002_003E", 
                                             "B25004_002E","B25004_003E",
                                             "B25004_004E","B25004_005E",
                                             # total housing unit
                                             "B25001_001E",
                                             # renter occupied 
                                             'B08137_003E'), 
          year=2019, state= 08, county= 013, geometry=T, output="wide") %>%
  st_transform(st_crs(boulder.sf)) %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B25026_001E, 
         Whites = B02001_002E,
         MedHHInc = B19013_001E, 
         MedRent = B25058_001E,
         TotalPoverty = B06012_002E,
         TotalVacant = B25002_003E,
         ForRent = B25004_002E,
         ForRentVac = B25004_003E,
         ForSale = B25004_004E,
         ForSaleVac = B25004_005E,
         TotalUnit = B25001_001E,
         RenterOccupied = B08137_003E
         ) %>%
  dplyr::select(-NAME, -starts_with("B")) %>%
  mutate(pctWhite = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, Whites / TotalPop,0),
         pctPoverty = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, TotalPoverty / TotalPop, 0),
         pctTotalVacant = ifelse(TotalUnit > 0, TotalVacant / TotalUnit * 100, 0),
         TotalOccupied = TotalUnit - TotalVacant,
        pctRenterOccupied = ifelse(TotalOccupied >0, RenterOccupied/TotalOccupied, 0)) %>%
  dplyr::select(-Whites, -TotalPoverty) 

projected.tracts2019 <-  
    tracts2019 %>%  
 st_transform(st_crs(boulder.sf))

2.2 Feature engineering

Feature engineering is the process of transforming raw data into relevant features when creating a prediction model. In this project, I took the internal house conditions, socio-economic factors, and proximity to amenities and public services into models and conducted feature engineering to improve algoriths performance. Especially, I developed nn_function as a feature to calculate the average nearest neighbor distance from each house to its k(k=1,2,3,4,5) nearest neighbor crimes.

st_c <- st_coordinates

boulder.sf <-
  boulder.sf %>% 
    mutate(
      health_nn1 = nn_function(st_c(boulder.s), st_c(Health_facility.sf), 1),
      health_nn2 = nn_function(st_c(boulder.s), st_c(Health_facility.sf), 2), 
      health_nn3 = nn_function(st_c(boulder.s), st_c(Health_facility.sf), 3), 
      health_nn4 = nn_function(st_c(boulder.s), st_c(Health_facility.sf), 4), 
      health_nn5 = nn_function(st_c(boulder.s), st_c(Health_facility.sf), 5))

2.3 Correlation matrix

After all the potential related features are set, I conducted exploratory analysis to generate proper feature combination. I created multiple correlation matrices to visualize the correlation between independent variables and develop scatter plots to visualize the linearity between independent variables and house prices.Finally, I selected variables which have lower correlation (\(-0.6<R^2<0.6\)) with other independent variables and linear relationship with dependent variable as the features in the prediction models.

2.3.1 All features

According the correlation matrix below, dark blue indicates two features are strongly and positively correlated with each other, while dark green indicates a strongly negative correlation. White means there is no correlation between the features.

numericVars.all<-
  select_if(all.feature.list,is.numeric)%>%
  na.omit()

ggcorrplot(
  round(cor(numericVars.all), 2), 
  p.mat = cor_pmat(numericVars.all),
  colors = c('#05A167', "white", '#6897BB'),
  lab_size = 1,
  tl.cex = 5,
  type="lower",
  insig = c("pch", "blank"), pch = 1, pch.col = "black", pch.cex =1) +  
  labs(title = "Correlation across numeric variables\n(All features)\n") +
  plotTheme()

According to the correlation matrix below, we can clearly see that the houses proximity to theaters has negative correlation with its distance to open space. And the houses proximity to school is highly and positively correlated with its distance to healthy care.

For the plots below,percentage of white people,number of bedroom,the quality code,and number of main floor were chosen as x axis and the house price was chosen as the y axis. The results showed that each of the independent variables is positively correlated with house price.

features <- c('percentage of White','bedroom number','quality code','main floor square')
names(features)<-c('pctWhite','nbrBedRoom','qualityCode','mainfloorSF')

price.house.plot <- 
  st_drop_geometry(train_data) %>%

03. Methods

Here, I adopted geospatial machine learning models to predict house price based on above data. I built a ordinary least squares regression model with several features,and then combined different features to optimization the model. The main measurements for the model performance include residual standard error, \(R^2\), mean absolute error(MAE), and p-value. MAE is calculated the mean absolute errors between actual values and predictive values. Residual standard is the standard deviation of the residual values, indicating how much the data points spread around the regression line. The p-value shows the probability that an observed data could have occur under the null hypothesis. \(R^2\) represents the proportion of the variance for a dependent variable that is explained by an independent variable or variables in a regression model.

4.6 Spatial Autocorrelation

I used three methods to detect spatial autocorrelation in the model.
01. Map of residuals: Map the residuals around the boulder;
02. Spatial lags plot: Map the average neighboring values of house prices;
03. Morans I: Map the correlation coefficient that measures the overall spatial autocorrelation of the data.

4.6.1 Map of residuals

By the map below we can see that the residuals tend to cluster in urban districts, northeastern and southeastern of Boulder, which indicates spatial autocorrelation.

map_residual<- ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data=boulder.boundary)+
  geom_sf(data=model_test2,
          aes(color=q5(SalePrice.Error)),
          show.legend = "point",size = 1)+  
                    scale_color_manual(values =  c(palette),
                     labels = qBr(model_test2,'SalePrice.Error'),
                     name = "Residuals") +
  labs(title = 'Map of residuals on test set\n') +
  mapTheme() + 
  plotTheme()
map_residual

4.6.2 Spatial lags

Spatial lag is a variable that calculates the average values of a location in certain neighborhood. Here, I used census tract units as the neighborhood. The figure belows plots SalePrice as a function of spatial lag, which indicates the dependencies exist in nearby neighborhoods.

## Spatial lag in errors: average errors in five nearest neighbors
k_nearest_neighbors = 5
# average errors in five nearest neighbors
coords.test <- st_centroid(st_geometry(model_test2),
                           of_largest_polygon=TRUE)

neighborList.test <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords.test, k_nearest_neighbors))

spatialWeights.test <- nb2listw(neighborList.test, style="W") 


model_test2$lagPriceError <- lag.listw(spatialWeights.test,model_test2$SalePrice.Error)

error.spatial.lag <- ggplot(model_test2, 
                            aes(x = lagPriceError, y = SalePrice.Error)) +
  geom_point(colour = "black") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "darkred") +
  labs(title = "Error on Test Set as a function of the Spatial Lag of Price\n",
       x = "Spatial lag of errors (Mean error of 5 nearest neighbors)",
       y = "Errors of Sale Price") +
  plotTheme()

error.spatial.lag

4.6.3 Morans I

The Morans I of Model 4 is 0.2383. The pseudo p-value is 0.001, which indicates that null hypothesis that the the house price is randomly distributed can be rejected.

moranTest <- moran.mc(model_test2$SalePrice.AbsError, 
                      spatialWeights.test, nsim = 999)

moran.plot <- ggplot(as.data.frame(moranTest$res[c(1:999)]), 
                     aes(moranTest$res[c(1:999)])) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = moranTest$statistic), colour = "orange",size=1) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(title="Observed and permuted Moran's I",
       subtitle= "Observed Moran's I in orange, I = 0.2383",
       x="Moran's I",
       y="Count") +
  plotTheme()
moran.plot

Here I compared the MAP and MAPE for baseline regression and neighborhood effect model. According to the table below, we can clearly see, the neighborhood effect model has lower MAP and MAPE with higher accuracy compared to baseline model.

     dplyr::select(# spatial features
                   MUSA_ID,
                   price,designCode,
            qualityCode,EffectiveYear,nbrBedRoom,mainfloorSF,landmark_nn2,  
 health_nn1, Tra_station_nn5, Openspace_nn5, Area_Trail_nn4,pctRenterOccupied,pctTotalVacant,pctWhite,pctPoverty,library_nn3,MedHHInc ) 
)


m2.boulder.test.nhood <-
  model_test %>% 
  mutate(Regression = "Neighborhood Effects",
         SalePrice.Predict = predict(m2.nhood, model_test),
         SalePrice.Error = price - SalePrice.Predict,
         SalePrice.AbsError = abs(price - SalePrice.Predict),
         SalePrice.APE = (abs(price - SalePrice.Predict)) / price) %>%
  filter(price < 5000000)


bothRegressions <- 
  rbind(
    dplyr::select(model_test2, starts_with("price"),starts_with("SalePrice"), Regression, MUSA_ID) ,
    dplyr::select(m2.boulder.test.nhood, starts_with("price"),starts_with("SalePrice"), Regression, MUSA_ID) )

st_drop_geometry(bothRegressions) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -Regression, -MUSA_ID) %>%
  filter(Variable == "SalePrice.AbsError" | Variable == "SalePrice.APE") %>%
  group_by(Regression, Variable) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(meanValue = mean(Value, na.rm = T)) %>%
  spread(Variable, meanValue) %>%
  kable(caption = '\nSummary of MAE, and MAPE by Regression Models') %>%
  kable_styling("striped", full_width = F)

4.10.2 Generalizability in income context

To further test the models generalizability, I split the dataset into high and low income groups by collecting income data from 2015-2019 ACS 5-year from tidycensus. The following figure shows that most household are high-income households, while the low-income households are clustered at the southwestern and northwestern areas.

census <-   train_data %>%

05. Discussion and conclusion

I would recommend the neighborhood effect model to Zillow, since it incorporates spatial features and performs well on either accuracy or generalization with fairly low MAPE.

There are several aspects could be done to improve the model performance in the future.

First, more features of such as crime rate should be included in the algorithms to construct the model from a more integrated perspective.

Second, the linear regression model I use here simplifies the complex patterns in the real-world case. Thus, the non-linear regression models should be implemented to capture data representation and forecast the house prices more accurately.
